{"title": "Player-Exclusive Mechanic", "content": "Designing Video Game A.I. is hard. Some are so competent as to render the game Nintendo Hard, while others are blatantly stupid. But in general, you expect computer-controlled characters in multiplayer games to be capable of doing everything the player can. This trope is for when they can't.\n\nThis is not about the player exploiting Good Bad Bugs, but rather when the item or ability in question is explicitly designed to be capable of something that both the AI and the player can do (sometimes depending on context), but the AI for some reason does not. This can be particularly infuriating (or alternatively, worthy of relief) if the action is an interface command. In some cases this may be an Anti-Frustration Feature, or a case of Dynamic Difficulty where the computer only starts using them when you get good. Sometimes general difficulty setting choice (the \"Easy\", \"Hard\", etc. settings) may also regulate what they can and cannot do.\n\u2022 Many non-Fighting Games featuring a block/counter mechanic only have the Player Character able to do it.\n\nDo note that this trope is clearer to see in multiplayer and/or competitive games (such as fighting, racing, rhythm, etc), since we can gauge out what the computer characters can, and should, do in any given situation. In single-player/non-competitive games (mainly action, platformers, etc.) the players are supposed to do things that the enemies cannot (and vice versa) and thus it's universal \u2014 the exception of this is the Mirror Boss or Super Powered Mooks, in which those characters look and act the same as the PC, except for some technical differences (whether they have an access to the things that the PC normally doesn't \u2014 Secret A.I. Moves \u2014 or conversely, they cannot do some things the PC can \u2014 this trope).\n\nAnother case is when a player character in the non-competitive games suddenly becomes a boss (especially when there's a selection of playable characters), or when a boss is Promoted to Playable; this follows the same convention as above. Just as bosses with Secret A.I. Moves are liable to have a Redemption Demotion when they're playable, bosses with this trope will have a Redemption Promotion.\n\nYet another case (in line with the above) is when you have someone who's normally playable as a Non-Player Companion, or vice versa. When it happens, said someone may not be able to use their full potential and abilities as opposed to when they're controlled directly by the player.\n\nAlso note that, in some cases, both this trope and Secret A.I. Moves can appear together.\n\nThe supertrope to some forms of Tactical Door Use. Compare Artificial Stupidity (aka \"Player Exclusive Tactics\") and A.I. Roulette (the latter when the AI chooses not to use the action randomly). Contrast Artificial Brilliance, My Rules Are Not Your Rules, and Secret A.I. Moves. This can potentially result in a Game-Breaker.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/PlayerExclusiveMechanic", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MasterOfOrion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Civilization", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/EuropaUniversalis", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/AssassinsCreedI", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/AssassinsCreed", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DynastyWarriors", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DynastyWarriors", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/MagicTheGathering", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/YuGiOhDarkDuelStories", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/StreetFighterII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/HalfLife1", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Left4Dead", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Left4Dead2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Halo2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Halo", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Borderlands", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TeamFortress2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Payday2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/CounterStrike", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Killzone", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Castlevania", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MegaManZX", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MegaManX", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/KirbysDreamLand3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/CrashTeamRacing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/LEGORacers", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/BigRigsOverTheRoadRacing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/SuperMarioKart", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/JakXCombatRacing", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PacManWorldRally", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Warcraft", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/StarCraftI", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/DawnOfWar", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/CommandAndConquerTiberianSun", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/CommandAndConquerRedAlert2", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/EmpireEarth", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FTLFasterThanLight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/EnterTheGungeon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Solatorobo", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/Persona3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/Pokemon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PokemonColosseum", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PokemonXDGaleOfDarkness", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/PokemonMysteryDungeon", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FinalFantasyXIII", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/GranblueFantasy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/MassEffect", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/MassEffect3", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TheElderScrollsIVOblivion", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TheElderScrollsVSkyrim", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/X", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/AceCombat04ShatteredSkies", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/OperationFlashpoint", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FTLFasterThanLight", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/EscapeVelocity", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/DungeonsAndDragons", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/TabletopGame/Eberron", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/TenMinuteSpaceStrategy", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Franchise/FireEmblem", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblemPathOfRadiance", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblemRadiantDawn", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/VideoGame/FireEmblemF